        <span>Hello</span>
        <span>নমস্কার</span>
        <span>నమస్కారం</span>
        <span>നമസ്കാരം</span>
        <span>નમસ્તે</span>
        <span>ਸਤ ਸ੍ਰੀ ਅਕਾਲ</span>
        <span>नमस्कार</span>
        <span>ନମସ୍କାର</span>
        <span>নমস্কাৰ</span>
        <span>ආයුබෝවන්</span>
        <span>स्वागतम्</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="hero-name">Grusha<br/>G S</h1>
      <p class="hero-tagline">
        I build AI products that work in the languages most of India actually speaks. Currently shipping multilingual voice systems at Shunya Labs.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-status">Open to product roles</div>
      <div class="hero-links">
        <a href="mailto:grushags90@gmail.com">Email</a>
        <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/grushags" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LinkedIn</a>
        <a href="https://github.com/Grusha15" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>
        <a href="https://huggingface.co/grushaaaaa" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hugging Face</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="about">
      <div class="section-label">Why product</div>
      <p>
        At every role I have held, the work I found most valuable was not the model training itself. It was the decisions that came before and after it.
      </p>
      <p>
        At Nasscom, I spent two years translating what industry leaders told us they needed into a structured research agenda that shaped national AI policy. Identifying which problems matter, in what order, for whom. That is product strategy work, even though my title said Tech Associate.
      </p>
      <p>
        At Shunya Labs, the pattern repeated. I sit between what the model can do and what the enterprise client actually needs. When Rakuten needed multilingual ASR, my job was not just to fine-tune Whisper. It was to figure out that brand-name accuracy mattered more than raw WER, to build the entity preservation layer that solved that specific business constraint, and to prioritize features under hardware limits the client would not negotiate on. That is product management. I have been doing it without the title.
      </p>
      <p>
        The case study on this site is an attempt to make that thinking visible. I picked a real product, a real user, and worked through the full loop: field research, problem framing, solution design, unit economics, and success metrics. The instinct I bring is asking what is not in the dashboard rather than what the dashboard says.
      </p>
      <p>
        The next role I am looking for is one where I do this work with a title and a team that matches it.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>